('D-014', 'F-2022-007', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Ironbridge Energy Partners - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Ironbridge Energy Partners\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2017\nTotal Exposure: $75,000,000 across 3 facilities\nRisk Rating: 1 (Superior)\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nIronbridge Energy Partners delivered another strong year in 2024 with revenue of $200M (flat year-over-year) and EBITDA of $34M (up 3%). The flat revenue reflects lower natural gas prices offset by volume growth from the newly acquired Permian Basin compression stations. EBITDA improvement was driven by operating efficiencies and lower maintenance costs.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Successfully integrated the 4-station Permian Basin compression complex acquired in Q2 2024\n2. Renewed 3 take-or-pay contracts representing $45M in annual revenue through 2028\n3. Completed $12M maintenance capex program on schedule and under budget\n4. Launched environmental monitoring initiative to reduce methane emissions by 30% by 2027\n\nCOVENANT COMPLIANCE:\nAll covenants in full compliance with substantial headroom. Leverage ratio of 2.10x vs. 3.50x maximum; interest coverage of 3.80x vs. 2.50x minimum.\n\nRISK ASSESSMENT:\nPrimary risk is commodity price exposure, though the borrower\'s contract structure (85% fixed-fee take-or-pay) significantly mitigates volume and pricing risk. The Permian Basin concentration (now 45% of assets) is noted as a geographic risk factor but is mitigated by the basin\'s long-term production outlook.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 1. Approve relationship renewal. Consider pricing reduction at next facility maturity given exemplary credit performance.',
 'Michael Torres, VP Credit', '2024-12-15'),

('D-015', 'F-2023-019', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Redwood Environmental Services - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Redwood Environmental Services\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2022\nTotal Exposure: $6,000,000 (1 facility)\nRisk Rating: 4 (Substandard) -- DOWNGRADED from 3 (Watch)\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nRedwood Environmental Services experienced significant financial deterioration in 2024. Revenue declined 18% to $27M (from $33M) due to delayed state contract renewals and loss of two municipal clients. EBITDA collapsed to $2.1M (from $5.3M), reflecting revenue loss combined with fixed cost structure. The company has been in continuous covenant default since Q1 2024.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS (NEGATIVE):\n1. California state budget cuts delayed $8M in planned remediation contracts by 12+ months\n2. Key project manager departed to competitor, taking two client relationships\n3. Equipment utilization dropped to 55% from 80% in 2023\n4. CEO/founder health concerns limiting engagement (key person risk materializing)\n5. Accounts payable stretching to 75+ days as cash flow tightens\n\nCOVENANT STATUS:\nFacility has been in default on leverage ratio and interest coverage covenants for three consecutive quarters. DSCR of 0.35x indicates inability to service debt from operations. The Q2 2024 EBITDA of $2.1M is $1.9M below the $4.0M minimum covenant.\n\nCOLLATERAL POSITION:\nEquipment appraisal updated in September 2024 shows forced liquidation value of $3.8M vs. outstanding balance of $5.8M, indicating a collateral shortfall of $2.0M. Personal guarantee from CEO has limited enforcement value given health situation.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Downgrade to Risk Rating 4 (Substandard). Transfer to Special Assets group for workout. Evaluate options including (i) structured paydown with extended amortization, (ii) sale of equipment fleet to satisfy debt, or (iii) UCC foreclosure if borrower becomes uncooperative. Reserve recommendation: 25% specific reserve ($1.45M).',
 'Sarah Chen, Senior Credit Analyst', '2024-12-20'),

('D-016', 'F-2024-021', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Coastal Hospitality Group - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Coastal Hospitality Group\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2020\nTotal Exposure: $23,000,000 across 2 facilities\nRisk Rating: 3 (Watch) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nCoastal Hospitality Group operates 8 boutique hotels and resorts along the Florida Gulf Coast. Revenue of $88M was flat year-over-year as strong winter season performance was offset by a weaker-than-expected summer due to Hurricane Milton disruptions in October 2024. EBITDA of $8.8M (10% margin) was stable but below the 12% industry benchmark for comparable resort operators.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Two properties sustained minor damage from Hurricane Milton, now fully repaired with insurance proceeds\n2. Renovation of the Sarasota flagship property completed on budget, driving 20% ADR increase\n3. Seasonal cash flow pattern remains pronounced -- Q1 and Q4 generate 75% of annual EBITDA\n4. Bridge loan for new Tampa Bay acquisition (F-2024-021) is progressing but lease-up slower than projected\n\nCOVENANT STATUS:\nThe bridge loan (F-2024-021) breached leverage ratio (4.50x vs. 4.00x max) and interest coverage (1.20x vs. 1.50x min) in Q4 2024 due to seasonal trough combined with hurricane-related disruption. The working capital revolver (F-2023-040) also breached leverage and fixed charge coverage. Management expects Q1 2025 performance to restore compliance as peak season begins.\n\nRISK ASSESSMENT:\nPrimary risks are (i) seasonal cash flow concentration, (ii) hurricane/climate exposure, and (iii) interest rate sensitivity on floating rate bridge debt. The Tampa Bay acquisition is 65% leased vs. the 80% underwriting assumption at 9 months post-closing.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 3 (Watch). Continue enhanced monitoring with monthly reporting. Revisit in Q2 2025 after peak season performance is measurable. If Q1 2025 fails to restore covenant compliance, recommend transfer to Special Assets.',
 'Michael Torres, VP Credit', '2024-12-18'),

-- ============================================================
-- BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSES
-- ============================================================

('D-017', 'F-2024-013', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Quantum Data Systems - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Quantum Data Systems\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: Jennifer Walsh\nDate: January 20, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nQuantum Data Systems is a SaaS company providing data analytics solutions to mid-market retailers. The company is experiencing a growth-to-profitability transition that is straining financial metrics.\n\nREVENUE ANALYSIS:\nQ4 2024 revenue of $7.8M represents 12% year-over-year growth but a deceleration from the 22% growth rate in Q4 2023. Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR) grew to $28M. Customer churn increased to 8% annually (from 5%), driven by competitive pressure from larger enterprise platforms offering bundled analytics.\n\nEBITDA BRIDGE:\nQ4 2024 EBITDA: $3.6M (annualized) vs. Q3 2024: $4.1M\n- Revenue growth: +$0.3M\n- Sales & marketing spend increase: -$0.5M (new enterprise sales team hired)\n- R&D investment: -$0.3M (platform modernization initiative)\n- Net impact: -$0.5M sequential decline\n\nADJUSTMENT ANALYSIS:\nManagement presented $0.8M in EBITDA add-backs including $0.4M in one-time recruiting costs and $0.4M in platform migration expenses. After review, the analyst accepts $0.4M (recruiting costs) as legitimate one-time items but rejects the platform migration add-back as a recurring investment required to maintain competitive positioning.\n\nLIQUIDITY ASSESSMENT:\nCash on hand: $1.2M (declining from $2.8M at Q2 2024). Monthly cash burn of $0.25M at current run rate. The term loan payment schedule creates a $1.5M principal payment due in April 2025. Without revenue acceleration or cost reduction, the company will face a liquidity shortfall by Q3 2025.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nEscalate to portfolio manager for discussion at next weekly risk meeting. The company needs either (i) an equity raise to fund the growth investment, (ii) a pivot to profitability that sacrifices growth, or (iii) a strategic sale. Current trajectory is unsustainable with existing debt structure.',
 'Jennifer Walsh, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-20'),

('D-018', 'F-2024-006', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Veridian Technologies - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Veridian Technologies\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: David Park\nDate: January 18, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nVeridian Technologies develops industrial IoT monitoring systems for manufacturing plants. The company continues to perform well with solid revenue growth and healthy margins, though capex investments for a new product line warrant monitoring.\n\nREVENUE ANALYSIS:\nQ4 2024 revenue of $12.5M (annualized $45M, up 15% YoY). Growth driven by expansion of existing customer deployments (land-and-expand model) and 8 new enterprise customer wins. Hardware revenue (40% of total) remained stable while software/subscription revenue (60%) grew 25%, improving overall margin profile.\n\nEBITDA ANALYSIS:\nTrailing 12-month EBITDA of $9.0M represents a 20% margin, up from 18% in 2023. The improvement reflects software revenue mix shift and operating leverage. Leverage ratio improved to 3.10x from 3.40x at origination, well within the 4.00x covenant.\n\nOPERATIONAL HIGHLIGHTS:\n- Customer retention rate: 95% (industry-leading)\n- Average contract value increased 18% to $180K annually\n- New predictive maintenance product in beta with 12 pilot customers\n- Hired VP Engineering from major industrial automation company\n\nRISK FACTORS:\n- R&D spend increasing to 18% of revenue (from 14%) for new product development\n- Supply chain: Key sensor components sourced from single supplier in Taiwan\n- Competition: Large industrial conglomerates entering the IoT monitoring space\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nNo action required. Continue standard quarterly monitoring. Consider proactive outreach regarding potential expansion of facility to fund accelerated growth -- strong candidate for equipment finance or expanded term loan.',
 'David Park, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-18'),

