('D-019', 'F-2023-009', 'amendment_letter',
 'First Amendment and Waiver: Cascade Paper & Packaging',
 'FIRST AMENDMENT AND LIMITED WAIVER TO CREDIT AGREEMENT\n\nDate: November 1, 2024\n\nThis Amendment waives the Events of Default arising from the Borrower\'s failure to comply with the Maximum Leverage Ratio and Minimum Fixed Charge Coverage Ratio for Q3 2024.\n\nAMENDMENTS:\n1. Maximum Leverage Ratio: Temporarily increased from 3.00x to 4.00x for Q3 2024 testing period only.\n2. Fixed Charge Coverage: Temporarily decreased from 1.10x to 0.90x for Q3 2024 testing period only.\n3. Advance Rate Reduction: From 82% to 75% effective immediately.\n4. Cash Dominion: Activated. All proceeds swept to lender-controlled account.\n5. Waiver Fee: $80,000 (1.0% of commitment).\n6. Financial Advisor: Borrower must retain a restructuring advisor acceptable to Lender within 30 days.\n\nThe Lender reserves all rights and remedies with respect to any future defaults. This waiver does not constitute a waiver of any other provision of the Credit Agreement.',
 'Legal Department', '2024-11-01'),

('D-020', 'F-2024-021', 'collateral_appraisal',
 'Collateral Appraisal: Coastal Hospitality - Tampa Bay Resort Property',
 'INDEPENDENT APPRAISAL REPORT\n\nProperty: Tampa Bay Waterfront Resort & Conference Center\nClient: Specialty Finance Direct Lending Group\nEffective Date: February 15, 2024\n\nPROPERTY DESCRIPTION:\nFull-service resort with 180 rooms, 12,000 SF conference center, pool complex, and marina with 40 wet slips. Located on 8 acres of Tampa Bay waterfront. Originally constructed in 2008, last renovated 2019.\n\nVALUATION:\n- As-Is Value (65% Occupied): $18,125,000 ($100,694/room)\n- As-Stabilized Value (85% Occupied): $24,500,000 ($136,111/room)\n\nMARKET OBSERVATIONS:\nTampa Bay hospitality market has recovered to 92% of pre-pandemic RevPAR levels. Luxury and upper-upscale segments outperforming, while select-service segment faces oversupply. The subject property\'s waterfront location and conference facilities provide competitive differentiation. Seasonal occupancy ranges from 85-95% (December-April) to 45-60% (June-September).',
 'HVS Hospitality Valuation Services', '2024-02-15'),

('D-021', 'F-2024-001', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Apex Manufacturing Corp - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Apex Manufacturing Corp\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: Jennifer Walsh\nDate: January 22, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nApex Manufacturing experienced margin pressure in Q4 2024 due to softening aerospace aftermarket demand and rising steel costs. While revenue remained stable at $85M annualized, EBITDA declined to $12.75M from $14.2M in 2023, pushing the leverage ratio to 3.65x -- slightly above the 3.50x covenant threshold.\n\nEBITDA BRIDGE (YoY):\n- Starting EBITDA (2023): $14,200,000\n- Aerospace aftermarket volume decline: -$1,200,000\n- Steel cost increases (net of pass-through): -$800,000\n- Automotive program wins: +$400,000\n- Operational efficiency gains: +$150,000\n- Ending EBITDA (2024): $12,750,000\n\nLEVERAGE ANALYSIS:\nTotal funded debt of $19.7M ($11.2M ABL + $8.5M term) against $12.75M EBITDA yields a leverage ratio of 1.55x on a total basis, though the term loan covenant tests at the entity level including the full ABL draw. The covenant amendment granted in January 2025 provides temporary relief (4.00x for Q4 2024, 3.75x for Q1 2025).\n\nOUTLOOK:\nManagement guidance for 2025 projects EBITDA recovery to $13.5-14.0M based on new automotive program launches in Q2 and moderating steel costs. If achieved, leverage would return below 3.50x by Q2 2025. The primary downside risk is further aerospace demand softening if the commercial aviation cycle decelerates.',
 'Jennifer Walsh, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-22'),

('D-022', 'F-2021-026', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Trident Defense Systems - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Trident Defense Systems\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2016\nTotal Exposure: $45,000,000 across 2 facilities\nRisk Rating: 1 (Superior) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nTrident Defense Systems is a defense electronics and communications systems manufacturer with $180M in annual revenue and $27M EBITDA. The company benefits from a robust backlog of $320M (1.8x revenue coverage) driven by increasing defense spending and modernization programs.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Won $85M multi-year contract for next-generation tactical communications systems\n2. Expanded secure manufacturing facility by 40,000 SF to accommodate new contract requirements\n3. Achieved CMMC Level 2 certification ahead of schedule, providing competitive advantage\n4. Revenue guidance for 2025 increased to $195-205M based on backlog conversion\n\nCOVENANT COMPLIANCE:\nAll covenants in compliance with significant headroom. Leverage ratio of 1.40x (limit: 3.00x); interest coverage of 5.20x (min: 2.50x). DSCR of 2.30x provides strong debt service capacity.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 1 (Superior). Exemplary credit -- longest-tenured relationship in the portfolio. Proactively offer expanded facility or improved pricing at next review to protect the relationship from competitive refinancing.',
 'James Rodriguez, Managing Director', '2024-12-10'),

('D-023', 'F-2023-005', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Pinnacle Logistics Group - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Pinnacle Logistics Group\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: David Park\nDate: February 3, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nPinnacle Logistics continues its downward trajectory with all three financial covenants in breach for Q4 2024. The combination of customer losses, elevated fuel costs, and incomplete acquisition integration has created an unsustainable capital structure. Immediate action required.\n\nREVENUE ANALYSIS:\nQ4 2024 revenue of $14.2M (annualized ~$57M) represents a 12% decline from $65M run rate in Q1 2024. The company lost two anchor customers (combined $7.5M annual revenue) who cited service reliability concerns related to driver shortages and dispatch system issues inherited from the Delta Transport acquisition.\n\nCASH FLOW ANALYSIS:\nOperating cash flow turned negative in Q4 2024 at -$0.4M. Key drivers:\n- Lower revenue with high fixed cost structure (terminals, leases)\n- Increased fuel costs ($0.15/mile above budget)\n- Deferred maintenance on fleet creating higher repair frequency\n- A/R days stretched to 52 from 38, indicating customer payment slowdowns\n\nBORROWING BASE EROSION:\nEligible receivables have declined from $12.8M to $9.6M, reducing borrowing availability. At the current 75% advance rate, maximum availability is $7.2M vs. $10.8M outstanding. The facility is currently over-advanced by $3.6M -- this creates an immediate liquidity event if a formal over-advance waiver is not granted.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nEscalate to Special Assets. The borrower cannot service its debt from operations and has exhausted borrowing availability. Options: (i) negotiate structured paydown with asset sales, (ii) bring in DIP financing and Chapter 11, or (iii) consensual liquidation of fleet assets (estimated recovery: $4-5M on $10.8M outstanding).',
 'David Park, Credit Analyst', '2025-02-03'),

('D-024', 'F-2022-014', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Heartland Grain Cooperative - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Heartland Grain Cooperative\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2018\nTotal Exposure: $31,000,000 across 2 facilities\nRisk Rating: 2 (Satisfactory) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nHeartland Grain Cooperative is a farmer-owned cooperative operating 12 grain elevators across Iowa and southern Minnesota. Revenue of $150M was up 5% year-over-year driven by strong harvest volumes, though commodity margins compressed slightly. EBITDA of $15M maintained 10% margins.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Completed $6M expansion of the Des Moines terminal, increasing storage capacity by 2M bushels\n2. Installed new grain drying technology reducing energy costs by 20% per bushel\n3. Member count increased to 1,200 farmers (from 1,100), expanding geographic coverage\n4. Signed 5-year rail transport agreement locking in favorable freight rates\n\nSEASONAL PATTERN NOTE:\nThe cooperative\'s asset-based line experiences significant seasonal fluctuations. Peak utilization occurs September-November during harvest when receivables and inventory peak. The current $18M outstanding (December snapshot) will typically decline to $8-10M by April as grain inventories are sold. This seasonal pattern has been consistent for 6 years.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 2 (Satisfactory). Stable agricultural credit with well-understood seasonal dynamics. Approve facility renewal at current terms.',
 'Sarah Chen, Senior Credit Analyst', '2024-12-12'),

('D-025', 'F-2024-028', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Clearwater Pharmaceuticals - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Clearwater Pharmaceuticals\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: Jennifer Walsh\nDate: January 25, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nClearwater Pharmaceuticals is an early-commercial-stage specialty pharma company with one FDA-approved product generating $35M in annual revenue. The company breached its leverage ratio and minimum EBITDA covenants in Q4 2024 as R&D spending for its Phase 2 pipeline candidate accelerated ahead of revenue growth.\n\nREVENUE ANALYSIS:\nQ4 2024 revenue of $9.2M (annualized $35M, up 8% YoY) was driven by continued adoption of the company\'s lead product for rare metabolic disorders. The growth rate decelerated from 25% in 2023 as the initial launch curve flattened. Management projects 15-20% growth in 2025 based on expanded payer coverage and new specialty pharmacy partnerships.\n\nEBITDA AND COVENANT ANALYSIS:\nReported EBITDA of $4.2M (annualized) vs. $7.0M covenant minimum. The shortfall is entirely attributable to a $3.5M increase in R&D spending for the Phase 2 clinical trial of CWP-201 (projected enrollment completion: Q3 2025). Excluding R&D investment, adjusted cash flow from the commercial business is $7.7M.\n\nThis creates a challenging analytical question: the R&D investment, if successful, dramatically increases enterprise value and our recovery potential. However, if the trial fails, the company becomes a single-product entity with limited growth runway.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nMaintain enhanced monitoring. Schedule management meeting to discuss (i) Phase 2 interim data readout expected in Q2 2025, (ii) funding plan for remaining trial costs, and (iii) whether an equity raise is planned. The covenant breach is driven by investment rather than operational deterioration, which argues for a constructive approach rather than enforcement.',
 'Jennifer Walsh, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-25'),

('D-026', 'F-2024-031', 'credit_committee_memo',
 'Credit Committee Memo: Vanguard IT Solutions - Term Loan',
 'CREDIT COMMITTEE MEMORANDUM\n\nBorrower: Vanguard IT Solutions\nFacility: $4M Senior Secured Term Loan\nPurpose: Working capital and strategic acquisition bridge\n\nDEAL RATIONALE:\nVanguard IT Solutions is a managed IT services provider serving small businesses in the Virginia/DC metro area. The term loan provides working capital to fund onboarding costs for a recently won 50-seat managed services contract and bridges potential acquisition of a complementary cybersecurity practice.\n\nRISK FACTORS:\n1. Small scale: $22M revenue with $4.4M EBITDA provides limited margin for error.\n2. Thin capitalization: Pro forma leverage of 4.8x at funding is near the 5.0x covenant maximum.\n3. Customer concentration: Government subcontracts represent 40% of revenue, creating contract renewal risk.\n4. Acquisition uncertainty: The target cybersecurity practice is under LOI but not yet closed. If the acquisition does not proceed, the loan is oversized for the existing business.\n5. Technology obsolescence: Rapid evolution in managed services (cloud migration, AI-driven operations) requires continuous investment.\n\nMITIGANTS:\n- Recurring revenue model with 90% retention rates\n- Growing demand for managed IT and cybersecurity services\n- Experienced management team with 20+ years in IT services\n- Personal guarantee from majority owner\n\nCREDIT COMMITTEE VOTE: Approved (3-2)\nDissent noted: Two members recommended declining due to thin capitalization and acquisition contingency. Approval conditioned on monthly reporting and prohibition on additional debt.\nConditions: Monthly financial reporting, quarterly board observer rights, negative covenant on additional indebtedness, use of proceeds restricted to approved purposes.',
 'David Park, Credit Analyst', '2024-07-15'),

('D-027', 'F-2024-029', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Horizon Renewable Energy - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Horizon Renewable Energy\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: David Park\nDate: January 28, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nHorizon Renewable Energy develops, owns, and operates community solar installations across the Southwest. The company continues to perform in line with expectations, with stable cash flows from long-term power purchase agreements (PPAs) and growing EBITDA as new installations reach commercial operation.\n\nREVENUE AND EBITDA:\nQ4 2024 revenue of $15.5M (annualized $58M, up 12% YoY). EBITDA of $8.7M (15% margin). Growth driven by 3 new solar installations reaching commercial operation in 2024 (aggregate 45 MW capacity). All installations are contracted under 20-year PPAs with investment-grade utilities.\n\nEQUIPMENT FINANCE FACILITY PERFORMANCE:\nThe $9M equipment finance facility (F-2024-029) funded panel and inverter procurement for the most recent installation. Collateral (solar equipment and land leases) has an appraised value of $14M, yielding a healthy 58% LTV. The equipment is performing at 98% of nameplate capacity.\n\nCOVENANT STATUS:\nLeverage ratio of 2.80x (limit: 4.00x) -- in compliance with 1.20x headroom. Cash flows from PPAs provide high visibility into debt service coverage.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nNo action required. Strong renewable energy credit with contracted cash flows. Proactively discuss expansion financing for 2025 pipeline of 60 MW across 4 planned installations. Candidate for expanded relationship.',
 'David Park, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-28'),

('D-028', 'F-2023-017', 'collateral_appraisal',
 'Collateral Appraisal: Summit Construction - Mixed-Use Development',
 'INDEPENDENT APPRAISAL REPORT\n\nProperty: Summit Mixed-Use Development - Lakewood, CO\nClient: Specialty Finance Direct Lending Group\nEffective Date: June 15, 2023\n\nPROPERTY DESCRIPTION:\nGround-up mixed-use development consisting of 120 residential units (market-rate apartments) over 25,000 SF of ground-floor retail space. Total building area: 185,000 SF on a 2.5-acre site in the Lakewood Town Center district.\n\nVALUATION:\n- As-Is Value (Under Construction): $18,000,000 (land + improvements to date)\n- As-Complete Value: $25,690,000\n- As-Stabilized Value (95% Occupancy): $29,400,000\n\nThe bridge loan of $20M against the as-complete value yields a 78% LTV. Against stabilized value, LTV improves to 68%.\n\nCONSTRUCTION STATUS:\nAs of the effective date, the project is 65% complete with structural work finished and MEP rough-in underway. Estimated completion: Q4 2023. Pre-leasing has commenced with 15 residential units and 2 retail spaces under LOI.\n\nMARKET OBSERVATIONS:\nLakewood multifamily market shows 4.2% vacancy with average rents of $1,850/month for comparable new construction. The retail submarket has limited new supply with asking rents of $28-32/SF NNN for ground-floor space.',
 'Rocky Mountain Appraisal Group', '2023-06-15'),

('D-029', 'F-2024-036', 'credit_committee_memo',
 'Credit Committee Memo: Ironbridge Energy Partners - Term Loan Expansion',
 'CREDIT COMMITTEE MEMORANDUM\n\nBorrower: Ironbridge Energy Partners\nFacility: $15M Senior Secured Term Loan (Incremental)\nPurpose: Fund pipeline lateral extension and compressor station upgrades\n\nDEAL RATIONALE:\nThis incremental term loan supports Ironbridge\'s expansion of the Permian Basin pipeline system with a 12-mile lateral extension connecting two new production sites. The expansion is underpinned by 10-year take-or-pay agreements with two investment-grade E&P operators representing $8M in annual fee revenue. Pro forma total exposure to Ironbridge increases to $75M across 3 facilities.\n\nRISK FACTORS:\n1. Concentration: Total exposure to single borrower increases to $75M (significant single-name concentration)\n2. Construction risk: 8-month construction timeline with permitting dependencies\n3. Regulatory: Pipeline permitting subject to environmental review\n\nMITIGANTS:\n- Contracted revenue covers 2.5x annual debt service on the incremental facility\n- Proven operator track record (15+ years, zero construction delays)\n- Pro forma leverage remains conservative at 2.15x (well within 3.50x covenant)\n- Cross-collateralized with existing compression station assets\n\nCREDIT COMMITTEE VOTE: Approved unanimously (5-0)\nNote: Committee acknowledged single-name concentration risk but approved given credit quality and contracted cash flows.',
 'James Rodriguez, Managing Director', '2023-12-20'),

('D-030', 'F-2023-032', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Patriot Staffing Services - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Patriot Staffing Services\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2020\nTotal Exposure: $12,000,000 (1 facility)\nRisk Rating: 3 (Watch) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nPatriot Staffing Services is a regional staffing company specializing in light industrial and administrative placements across Pennsylvania and New Jersey. Revenue of $82M was flat year-over-year as a softening labor market reduced temporary placement demand. EBITDA of $4.92M (6% margin) is thin for a staffing company and reflects competitive pricing pressure.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Won contract with regional hospital system for nurse staffing (estimated $8M annual revenue)\n2. Lost 2 industrial staffing clients to lower-priced national competitors\n3. Workers compensation claims increased 15% year-over-year, pressuring margins\n4. Invested in new applicant tracking system to improve candidate matching\n\nCOVENANT STATUS:\nAll covenants in compliance but with limited headroom. Leverage ratio of 3.20x vs. 4.00x maximum. The ABL borrowing base provides adequate liquidity with $2.4M of unused availability.\n\nRISK ASSESSMENT:\nThe staffing industry is cyclically sensitive and Patriot operates in the most commoditized segments (light industrial, administrative). The healthcare staffing expansion provides margin diversification but introduces regulatory complexity. The company\'s thin margins leave little buffer against economic slowdown.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 3 (Watch). The credit is performing but structurally thin. Monitor the healthcare staffing ramp closely -- if successful, it could justify an upgrade to Risk Rating 2. If the industrial staffing decline continues, discuss proactive facility reduction.',
 'Sarah Chen, Senior Credit Analyst', '2024-12-14'),

-- Additional documents for search depth
('D-031', 'F-2024-002', 'covenant_compliance_certificate',
 'Q4 2024 Covenant Compliance Certificate: Apex Manufacturing Corp',
 'COVENANT COMPLIANCE CERTIFICATE\n\nDate: January 28, 2025\nBorrower: Apex Manufacturing Corp\nFacility: $10M Term Loan (F-2024-002)\nReporting Period: Q4 2024\n\n1. MAXIMUM LEVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement (as amended): Not to exceed 4.00x\n   Actual: 3.65x\n   Status: IN COMPLIANCE (per First Amendment terms)\n   Note: Would have been non-compliant under original 3.50x covenant\n\n2. MINIMUM INTEREST COVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement: Not less than 2.00x\n   Actual: 2.40x\n   Status: IN COMPLIANCE\n   Headroom: 0.40x\n\nThe Borrower notes that Q4 results reflect the seasonal trough in aerospace aftermarket demand and elevated steel costs. Management projects improvement in Q1 2025 based on new automotive program launches and moderating input costs. The temporary covenant increase to 4.00x provided adequate headroom for the seasonal dip.',
 'Mark Anderson, CFO - Apex Manufacturing Corp', '2025-01-28'),

('D-032', 'F-2024-031', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Vanguard IT Solutions - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Vanguard IT Solutions\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: David Park\nDate: February 1, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nVanguard IT Solutions breached both the leverage ratio (5.20x vs. 5.00x max) and minimum EBITDA ($2.8M vs. $3.0M min) covenants in Q4 2024. The target cybersecurity acquisition fell through in November when the seller accepted a competing offer, leaving the company with an oversized debt load relative to its standalone business.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n- Cybersecurity acquisition terminated November 15, 2024\n- Two government subcontracts not renewed, reducing annual revenue by $2.2M\n- New 50-seat managed services contract ramping slower than projected (60% of target utilization)\n- Cash position declined to $0.4M from $1.1M at Q3\n\nLIQUIDITY CONCERNS:\nAt current burn rate, the company has approximately 4 months of liquidity runway. The Q1 2025 principal payment of $250K will further strain cash position. Management is exploring a Series A equity raise but has not yet engaged an investment bank.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nEscalate to portfolio manager. This credit is deteriorating rapidly and the original investment thesis (acquisition-driven growth) has failed. Without the cybersecurity acquisition, the company lacks the scale to support $4M in debt. Options: (i) negotiate accelerated paydown from any proceeds if the company raises equity, (ii) require personal guarantee enforcement, or (iii) begin exit discussions if Q1 2025 does not show improvement.',
 'David Park, Credit Analyst', '2025-02-01'),

('D-033', 'F-2023-017', 'borrower_financial_analysis',
 'Quarterly Financial Analysis: Summit Construction Group - Q4 2024',
 'BORROWER FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\n\nBorrower: Summit Construction Group\nPeriod: Q4 2024\nAnalyst: Jennifer Walsh\nDate: January 30, 2025\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY:\nSummit Construction Group is a commercial general contractor and real estate developer based in Colorado. The company performed solidly in 2024 with $110M revenue and $11M EBITDA (10% margin). The real estate bridge loan for the Lakewood mixed-use project is nearing maturity with a successful lease-up.\n\nBRIDGE LOAN STATUS (F-2023-017):\nThe Lakewood mixed-use development is now 92% leased (residential) and 85% leased (retail), exceeding the 90%/80% stabilization thresholds. Management has engaged a CMBS conduit for permanent financing with indicative terms of 6.5% fixed rate, 25-year amortization, 10-year term. Expected closing: Q2 2025. This would fully retire the $18.5M bridge loan.\n\nCONSTRUCTION BACKLOG:\nNew construction backlog of $85M provides 9 months of revenue visibility. Includes 2 new multifamily projects and a medical office building. Gross margins on construction contracts averaging 12%, in line with historical performance.\n\nRECOMMENDATION:\nNo action required. Monitor bridge loan refinancing progress. The permanent financing take-out should close within the current maturity date. If delayed, a 6-month extension at current terms would be reasonable given the strong lease-up performance.',
 'Jennifer Walsh, Credit Analyst', '2025-01-30'),

('D-034', 'F-2022-033', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Evergreen Timber Products - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Evergreen Timber Products\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2019\nTotal Exposure: $14,000,000 across 2 facilities\nRisk Rating: 2 (Satisfactory) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nEvergreen Timber Products operates sustainable forestry and lumber processing operations in Washington state. Revenue of $53M (up 6% YoY) and EBITDA of $7.95M (15% margin) reflect recovery in residential construction demand and favorable lumber pricing. The company manages 45,000 acres of certified sustainable timberland.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Lumber prices stabilized after 2023 volatility, improving margin predictability\n2. Opened new kiln-drying facility, increasing processing capacity by 25%\n3. Received FSC Chain of Custody recertification (competitive differentiator for premium buyers)\n4. Secured 3-year supply agreement with national homebuilder at favorable terms\n\nCOVENANT COMPLIANCE:\nAll covenants in compliance. Leverage ratio of 2.10x vs. 3.50x maximum. The ABL facility utilization is moderate at 70% ($7M drawn on $10M commitment).\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 2 (Satisfactory). Stable forestry credit with tangible collateral (timberland + equipment). The new kiln-drying facility positions the company for margin expansion. Consider equipment finance opportunity for the planned pellet mill project discussed by management.',
 'Michael Torres, VP Credit', '2024-12-16'),

-- Additional covenant certificates for search variety
('D-035', 'F-2024-028', 'covenant_compliance_certificate',
 'Q4 2024 Covenant Compliance Certificate: Clearwater Pharmaceuticals',
 'COVENANT COMPLIANCE CERTIFICATE\n\nDate: January 28, 2025\nBorrower: Clearwater Pharmaceuticals\nFacility: $6M Term Loan (F-2024-028)\nReporting Period: Q4 2024\n\n1. MAXIMUM LEVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement: Not to exceed 4.00x\n   Actual: 4.30x\n   Status: NOT IN COMPLIANCE\n   Variance: 0.30x over limit\n\n2. MINIMUM EBITDA (Trailing 12 months)\n   Covenant Requirement: Not less than $5,000,000\n   Actual: $4,200,000\n   Status: NOT IN COMPLIANCE\n   Variance: $800,000 below requirement\n\nNOTES:\nThe covenant breaches are driven by accelerated R&D spending for the Phase 2 clinical trial of CWP-201, not by deterioration of the commercial business. Revenue from the approved product grew 8% in Q4. The Borrower expects Phase 2 interim data in Q2 2025 and is exploring a Series B equity raise to fund remaining development costs without further leveraging the balance sheet.\n\nThe Borrower requests a temporary covenant amendment to increase the leverage ratio maximum to 5.00x and reduce the minimum EBITDA threshold to $3,500,000 for Q4 2024 and Q1 2025, reverting to original levels thereafter.',
 'Amanda Liu, CFO - Clearwater Pharmaceuticals', '2025-01-28'),

('D-036', 'F-2024-013', 'covenant_compliance_certificate',
 'Q4 2024 Covenant Compliance Certificate: Quantum Data Systems',
 'COVENANT COMPLIANCE CERTIFICATE\n\nDate: January 22, 2025\nBorrower: Quantum Data Systems\nFacility: $5M Term Loan (F-2024-013)\nReporting Period: Q4 2024\n\n1. MAXIMUM LEVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement: Not to exceed 4.50x\n   Actual: 4.80x\n   Status: NOT IN COMPLIANCE\n   Variance: 0.30x over limit\n\n2. MINIMUM EBITDA (Trailing 12 months)\n   Covenant Requirement: Not less than $4,000,000\n   Actual: $3,600,000\n   Status: NOT IN COMPLIANCE\n   Variance: $400,000 below requirement\n\nNOTES:\nThe covenant breaches reflect the company\'s ongoing growth-to-profitability transition. Management invested heavily in a new enterprise sales team and platform modernization in H2 2024, which depressed near-term EBITDA. ARR growth of 12% and 8 new enterprise customer wins demonstrate the investment is gaining traction.\n\nThe Borrower is evaluating strategic options including a potential Series A equity raise or strategic partnership. Management will present a detailed remediation plan at the quarterly review meeting scheduled for February 15, 2025.',
 'Kevin Moore, CFO - Quantum Data Systems', '2025-01-22'),

('D-037', 'F-2022-007', 'covenant_compliance_certificate',
 'Q4 2024 Covenant Compliance Certificate: Ironbridge Energy Partners',
 'COVENANT COMPLIANCE CERTIFICATE\n\nDate: January 20, 2025\nBorrower: Ironbridge Energy Partners\nFacility: $35M Working Capital Revolver (F-2022-007)\nReporting Period: Q4 2024\n\n1. MAXIMUM LEVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement: Not to exceed 3.50x\n   Actual: 2.10x\n   Status: IN COMPLIANCE\n   Headroom: 1.40x\n\n2. MINIMUM INTEREST COVERAGE RATIO\n   Covenant Requirement: Not less than 2.50x\n   Actual: 3.80x\n   Status: IN COMPLIANCE\n   Headroom: 1.30x\n\nThe Borrower continues to demonstrate strong financial performance with all covenants in compliance and substantial headroom. The recently completed Permian Basin lateral extension is operational and generating fee revenue in line with projections.',
 'Patricia Wells, CFO - Ironbridge Energy Partners', '2025-01-20'),

('D-038', 'F-2024-021', 'amendment_letter',
 'First Amendment: Coastal Hospitality Group - Bridge Loan',
 'FIRST AMENDMENT TO CREDIT AGREEMENT\n\nDate: February 10, 2025\n\nThis Amendment amends the Credit Agreement dated March 1, 2024 between Coastal Hospitality Group ("Borrower") and the Lender regarding the $15M Real Estate Bridge Loan (F-2024-021).\n\nWAIVER:\nThe Lender waives the Events of Default arising from failure to comply with the Maximum Leverage Ratio and Minimum Interest Coverage covenants for Q4 2024.\n\nAMENDMENTS:\n1. Leverage Ratio: Temporarily increased from 4.00x to 5.00x for Q4 2024 and Q1 2025.\n2. Interest Coverage: Temporarily decreased from 1.50x to 1.10x for Q4 2024 and Q1 2025.\n3. Seasonal Adjustment: For future Q3 and Q4 testing periods (June-December), covenant levels will be tested on a trailing 12-month basis rather than quarterly to account for seasonal cash flow patterns.\n4. Waiver Fee: $75,000 (0.5% of commitment).\n5. Appraisal Update: Borrower must deliver an updated property appraisal by April 1, 2025.\n\nRATIONALE:\nThe seasonal adjustment recognizes the inherent cash flow pattern of a Florida Gulf Coast hospitality operation. Peak season (December-April) generates the majority of annual EBITDA, and quarterly testing during the summer trough creates artificial covenant pressure that does not reflect annual credit quality.',
 'Legal Department', '2025-02-10'),

('D-039', 'F-2023-005', 'collateral_appraisal',
 'Collateral Appraisal: Pinnacle Logistics - Fleet and Equipment',
 'INDEPENDENT APPRAISAL REPORT\n\nSubject: Trucking Fleet and Warehouse Equipment\nClient: Specialty Finance Direct Lending Group\nEffective Date: December 1, 2024\nPrepared by: National Equipment Appraisal Services\n\nASSET SUMMARY:\n- Class 8 Tractors (18 units, 2019-2022 model years): $2,880,000\n- Dry Van Trailers (35 units, 2018-2023): $1,400,000\n- Refrigerated Trailers (8 units, 2020-2022): $640,000\n- Warehouse Equipment (forklifts, conveyors, racking): $480,000\n- Dispatch and GPS Systems: $120,000\n\nTOTAL ORDERLY LIQUIDATION VALUE: $5,520,000\nTOTAL FORCED LIQUIDATION VALUE: $4,140,000\n\nNOTES:\nFleet condition is mixed. Several units show deferred maintenance consistent with cost-cutting measures. Three tractors have exceeded recommended overhaul intervals. Trailer fleet is in serviceable condition. Warehouse equipment at the Atlanta terminal is modern (2022 installation) while the Savannah location uses older equipment approaching end of useful life.\n\nThe orderly liquidation value assumes a 90-day marketing period through established equipment auction channels. Forced liquidation assumes a 30-day timeline with discounted pricing.\n\nCOMPARISON TO OUTSTANDING DEBT:\nOutstanding balance (F-2023-005): $10,800,000\nOrderly liquidation value: $5,520,000\nCollateral coverage: 51%\nShortfall: $5,280,000\n\nThe tangible asset base provides partial recovery but does not fully cover the outstanding obligation. The borrower\'s receivables (separately pledged under the ABL formula) provide additional recovery potential.',
 'National Equipment Appraisal Services', '2024-12-01'),

('D-040', 'F-2024-038', 'annual_review',
 'Annual Credit Review: Liberty Aerospace Components - 2024',
 'ANNUAL CREDIT REVIEW\n\nBorrower: Liberty Aerospace Components\nReview Date: December 2024\nRelationship Since: 2017\nTotal Exposure: $20,000,000 across 2 facilities\nRisk Rating: 1 (Superior) -- MAINTAINED\n\nFINANCIAL PERFORMANCE SUMMARY:\nLiberty Aerospace Components manufactures precision-machined components for commercial and military aircraft engines. Revenue of $68M (up 8% YoY) and EBITDA of $10.2M (15% margin) reflect strong demand from both OEM production ramps and aftermarket services.\n\nKEY DEVELOPMENTS:\n1. Won sole-source position on next-generation narrow-body engine turbine blade program\n2. Aftermarket revenue grew 15% as aging fleet drives maintenance demand\n3. Achieved AS9100 Rev D recertification with zero nonconformities\n4. Invested $2.5M in 5-axis CNC machining center, expanding high-value capability\n\nCOVENANT COMPLIANCE:\nAll covenants in compliance with significant headroom. Leverage ratio of 1.60x vs. 3.00x maximum. The ABL facility is conservatively utilized at 70%.\n\nRISK ASSESSMENT:\nLiberty benefits from high barriers to entry (aerospace certifications, customer qualification processes) and long product life cycles. The sole-source engine program win provides 15+ years of contracted volume. Primary risk is aerospace cycle downturn, though the company\'s balanced OEM/aftermarket mix provides natural hedging.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Maintain Risk Rating 1 (Superior). Outstanding credit with strong competitive position. The new term loan facility (F-2024-038) funded the CNC investment and is performing as underwritten. Proactively discuss further expansion financing as the engine program ramps to full production in 2026.',
 'James Rodriguez, Managing Director', '2024-12-11');
